[Board "2"]
[Dealer "W"]
[Vulnerable "NS"]
[Deal "W:A.AK6.AKQ974.AQ9 K974.T954.82.KT2 862.J3.JT65.7643 QJT53.Q872.3.J85"]
[Declarer "E"]
[Contract "6D"]
[Result ""]
[Auction "W"]
2C pass 2D pass 3D pass 4D pass 6D pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 2, chOption: E, chBasis: S, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:1, nBasis: 2, nRot: 3, useStandardVul: true"]
[Category "Declarer Play"]
[Difficulty "advanced"]
[SkillPath "declarer_play/elimination_plays"]
[Student "S"]
{You naturally respond 2\D to West's strong 2\C opener. Before you know it you are playing a slam - with your mighty 2-point hand! East plays 6\D. South leads the \SQ.

If the contract appears to depend upon a finesse, try to find another way. Here, you can always try the \C finesse, but maybe you can eliminate \Ss and see what happens.

Win the \SA, play the \D4 to the \D10, and ruff a \S with the \DQ. Both opponents followed to the trump. 

Play the \D7 to the \DJ and ruff the last \S with the \DK.

Having eliminated the \Ds and \Ss, now remove the \Hs. Play \HA, \HK, and ruff a \H. 

At last it is time to play \Cs. Lead a \C from your hand and play dummy's \C9 if South plays low. North will win the trick but will be end-played, forced to either play a \C back to dummy's \C A Q, or give you a ruff-sluff. 

If South puts on either the \CT or \CJ you play dummy's \CQ. If North can win with the \CK he will once again be end-played, forced to either play a \C back to dummy's \CA 9, or give you a ruff-sluff.

The A Q 9 combination is interesting. Obviously if you have A Q 10 it works very well in an end-play situation. 

As you see, A Q 9 actually works just as well.}
[Play "W"]SQ

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "3"]
[Dealer "N"]
[Vulnerable "None"]
[Deal "N:Q94.AJ63.A72.K64 J75.T54.K93.Q985 KT2.KQ982.854.A3 A863.7.QJT6.JT72"]
[Declarer "S"]
[Contract "4H"]
[Result ""]
[Auction "N"]
1C pass 1H pass 2H pass 4H pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 3, chOption: S, chBasis: S, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:2, nBasis: 2, nRot: 0, useStandardVul: true"]
[Category "Declarer Play"]
[Difficulty "advanced"]
[SkillPath "declarer_play/elimination_plays"]
[Student "S"]
{South is to play 4\H. West leads the \DQ.  

You have two \D losers that you can't escape, as well as the \SA. So you must arrange your play so you don't lose a trick to the \SJ. That could mean you will finesse one defender for that card, but it would be a lot better if you could make the defense play \Ss first.

There is no reason to hold up so take your \DA and pull trumps, East showing up with three of them.

Now eliminate \Cs by playing \CA, \CK, and ruffing a \C.

The stage is now set for the throw-in. Be <b>SURE</b> to lead a \D for the throw-in, not a \S.

The defense will win the \D and can then take another \D trick if they like. But then they will have to play a \S (or give you a ruff-sluff). And as long as they start the \Ss you are assured that you will lose only one \S trick, the \SA.

Assume West is on lead for the first \S play.

If he leads the \SA it sets up both the \SK and \SQ so you only have one \S loser. If he leads low you also play low from dummy and East must play the \SJ to prevent you getting a trick with the \ST. Again you only lose one \S.

If East makes the first play by leading a low \S you play low from your hand. West must go up with the \SA to stop you from getting a trick with dummy's \S9. Then your \SK and \SQ will win two tricks.}
[Play "W"]DQ

