1C 1S 2S pass 3C pass 5C pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 5, chOption: N, chBasis: S, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:0, nBasis: 2, nRot: 2, useStandardVul: true"]
[Category "Declarer Play"]
[Difficulty "advanced"]
[SkillPath "declarer_play/elimination_plays"]
[Student "S"]
{South's cue-bid shows a limit raise or better (11 points) in \Cs. North is to play 5\C. East leads the \SQ, West takes the \SA and returns the \S6 to your \SK.  

You have lost one trick already and have a possible loser in trumps and another possible loser in \Hs. Both loserscan be avoided with successful finesses. The problem with the \C finesse is that East made an overcall so he is more likely to hold the \CK. If you don't try the \C finesse you may be able to throw a defender in with the \CK at a time when he will have to help you with his next play.

After winning the \SK immediately play the \CA.

It would have been nice to see the \CK fall, but it didn't. So play a small \D to dummy's \DA and play the \S9, ruffing in your hand.

Eliminate the \Ds by playing \DK, then ruffing your last \D in dummy.

You have done all the eliminating, time to throw in somebody. Play a \C.

Whichever defender had the \CK is now on lead, but wishes he wasn't. If he plays a \H  you get a free finesse. If he plays anything else you get a ruff-sluff.

If you had finessed for the \CK East would have won the trick and been able to make a safe exit, probably with his other \C.

You would then have been forced to rely on the \H finesse, and with East being the defender who showed some strength, you would likely have finessed through him.

About the only way the elimination/throw-in could fail is if the \Cs split 3-0. Then, if you play Ace and another the defender who wins would use his third \C as a safe exit.}
[Play "W"]SQ

