pass 1NT pass 3H pass 4H pass 5C pass 6H pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 6, chOption: E, chBasis: S, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:1, nBasis: 2, nRot: 3, useStandardVul: true"]
[Category "Declarer Play"]
[Difficulty "advanced"]
[SkillPath "declarer_play/elimination_plays"]
[Student "S"]
{Your 3\H bid is a slam suggestion. After you show the \CA partner wastes no time in bidding it.

East is to play 6\H. South leads the \SK.

This is a good slam. You have only two possible \C losers, and by taking two \C finesses you have an excellent chance of success. But by using an elimination play you will have a sure thing. 

Win the \SA and ruff a \S with a \H honor.

Play a small \H to dummy's \H9 and ruff another \S. Both defenders followed to the trump play.

Play another \H to dummy's \H10 and ruff the last \S.

Play the \DA and \DK.

Conveniently in dummy, you play a \C and insert the \CT if North plays low.

[showcards N:HA,H6,C7,C6 S:HK,HQ,CA,CQ]

South will probably win this trick. If he wins with the \CK then your hand is good. If he wins with the \CJ then he is end-played, forced to either lead a \C into your \C A Q or to give you a ruff-sluff.

You probably noticed that you could have finessed your \CQ on the first \C play and pulled off the end-play just as effectively. But there is an advantage to making the first finesse with the \CT.

If North just happens to hold both the \CK and \CJ you will make all thirteen tricks if your first finesse is with the \CT!}
[Play "W"]SK

